SENTENCE so now that we've discussed how people in ancient societies tamed animals like cows and chickens for food and other uses .
SENTENCE i'd like to talk about an ancient culture that domesticated horses .
SENTENCE it's the botai people .
SENTENCE the botai culture thrived over 5 ,     years ago in central asia ,  in what is now northern kazakhstan .
SENTENCE pretty much all of what we know about the botai comes from three archaeological sites .
SENTENCE and we learned that the botai were able to build large perennial villages ,  sometimes with hundreds of homes .
SENTENCE we also found horse bones at these sites and these can be traced back to the time of the botai settlements .
SENTENCE the climate that the botai culture lived in it was harsh .
SENTENCE and the botai people they didn't really seem to have much in the way of agriculture going on .
SENTENCE so their whole economy was really based on horses .
SENTENCE and because horses can withstand the tough climate ,  they can survive ice storms and they don't need heated barns ,  the botai people could settle in one place and rely on the horses for food ,  clothing and transportation .
SENTENCE so the botai were the first to domesticate horses ?
SENTENCE well ,  we are pretty sure that horses were first domesticated a bit earlier ,  to the northwest ,  in the area that is now ukraine and western russia .
SENTENCE it's quite possible that some of those people later migrated east to kazakhstan .
SENTENCE but what exactly tells us that these botai people ,  that the horses in their area were really domesticated ?
SENTENCE as with most ancient history ,  there is not much that we can be certain about .
SENTENCE but we know there was a significant population of wild horses in that area .
SENTENCE so there were plenty of opportunities for the botai people to find horses to domesticate .
SENTENCE we also know that horse milk was an important source of food for the botai people .
